In this article, President Barack Obama proclaims December 10, 2013, as Human Rights Day and the week beginning December 10, 2013, as Human Rights Week. The article highlights the importance of the Universal Declaration of Human Rights, which recognizes every person's right to liberty, equality, and justice under the law. It emphasizes that regardless of race, creed, sexual orientation, gender identity, or income level, all individuals share the freedoms of expression, religion, assembly, and association. However, it also acknowledges that in many parts of the world, people are still persecuted for their beliefs, imprisoned for their ideals, and punished for their convictions. The article calls for a commitment to securing threatened or denied freedoms, breaking down prejudice, amplifying voices calling for change, and supporting the principles of the Universal Declaration of Human Rights.